[src:dynamical-systems-math/lyapunov-stability] In fact, $N=0$ is uniformly stable and is asymptotically stable.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The **phase space** of a physical system is the set of all possible physical states of the system when described by a given parameterization.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Each possible state corresponds uniquely to a point in the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] For mechanical systems, the phase space usually consists of all possible values of the position and momentum parameters.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] It is the direct product of direct space and reciprocal space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The concept of phase space was developed in the late 19th century by Ludwig Boltzmann, Henri Poincaré, and Josiah Willard Gibbs.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In a phase space, every degree of freedom or parameter of the system is represented as an axis of a multidimensional space; a one-dimensional system is called a phase line, while a two-dimensional system is called a phase plane.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] For every possible state of the system or allowed combination of values of the system's parameters, a point is included in the multidimensional space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The system's evolving state over time traces a path (a **phase-space trajectory** for the system) through the high-dimensional space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The phase-space trajectory represents the set of states compatible with starting from one particular initial condition, located in the full phase space that represents the set of states compatible with starting from *any* initial condition.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] As a whole, the phase diagram represents all that the system can be, and its shape can easily elucidate qualities of the system that might not be obvious otherwise.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] A phase space may contain a great number of dimensions.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In classical mechanics, any choice of generalized coordinates *q**i* for the position (i.e. coordinates on configuration space) defines conjugate generalized momenta *p**i*, which together define co-ordinates on phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The motion of an ensemble of systems in this space is studied by classical statistical mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The local density of points in such systems obeys Liouville's theorem, and so can be taken as constant.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Within the context of a model system in classical mechanics, the phase-space coordinates of the system at any given time are composed of all of the system's dynamic variables.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Because of this, it is possible to calculate the state of the system at any given time in the future or the past, through integration of Hamilton's or Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] For simple systems, there may be as few as one or two degrees of freedom.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] One degree of freedom occurs when one has an autonomous ordinary differential equation in a single variable, $dy/dt=f(y),$ with the resulting one-dimensional system being called a phase line, and the qualitative behaviour of the system being immediately visible from the phase line.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The simplest non-trivial examples are the exponential growth model/decay (one unstable/stable equilibrium) and the logistic growth model (two equilibria, one stable, one unstable).
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The phase space of a two-dimensional system is called a phase plane, which occurs in classical mechanics for a single particle moving in one dimension, and where the two variables are position and velocity.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In this case, a sketch of the phase portrait may give qualitative information about the dynamics of the system, such as the limit cycle of the Van der Pol oscillator shown in the diagram.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Here the horizontal axis gives the position, and vertical axis the velocity.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] As the system evolves, its state follows one of the lines (trajectories) on the phase diagram.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] A plot of position and momentum variables as a function of time is sometimes called a **phase plot** or a **phase diagram**.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] However the latter expression, "phase diagram", is more usually reserved in the physical sciences for a diagram showing the various regions of stability of the thermodynamic phases of a chemical system, which consists of pressure, temperature, and composition.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In mathematics, a phase portrait is a geometric representation of the orbits of a dynamical system in the phase plane.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Each set of initial conditions is represented by a different point or curve.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Phase portraits are an invaluable tool in studying dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] They consist of a plot of typical trajectories in the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] This reveals information such as whether an attractor, a repellor or limit cycle is present for the chosen parameter value.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The concept of topological equivalence is important in classifying the behaviour of systems by specifying when two different phase portraits represent the same qualitative dynamic behavior.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] An attractor is a stable point which is also called a "sink".
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The repeller is considered as an unstable point, which is also known as a "source".
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] A phase portrait graph of a dynamical system depicts the system's trajectories (with arrows) and stable steady states (with dots) and unstable steady states (with circles) in a phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In classical statistical mechanics (continuous energies) the concept of phase space provides a classical analog to the partition function (sum over states) known as the phase integral.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Instead of summing the Boltzmann factor over discretely spaced energy states (defined by appropriate integer quantum numbers for each degree of freedom), one may integrate over continuous phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Such integration essentially consists of two parts: integration of the momentum component of all degrees of freedom (momentum space) and integration of the position component of all degrees of freedom (configuration space).
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Once the phase integral is known, it may be related to the classical partition function by multiplication of a normalization constant representing the number of quantum energy states per unit phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] This normalization constant is simply the inverse of the Planck constant raised to a power equal to the number of degrees of freedom for the system.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In quantum mechanics, the coordinates *p* and *q* of phase space normally become Hermitian operators in a Hilbert space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] But they may alternatively retain their classical interpretation, provided functions of them compose in novel algebraic ways (through Groenewold's 1946 star product).
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] This is consistent with the uncertainty principle of quantum mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Every quantum mechanical observable corresponds to a unique function or distribution on phase space, and conversely, as specified by Hermann Weyl (1927) and supplemented by John von Neumann (1931); Eugene Wigner (1932); and, in a grand synthesis, by H.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Moyal (1949), these completed the foundations of the **phase-space formulation of quantum mechanics**, a complete and logically autonomous reformulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Expectation values in phase-space quantization are obtained isomorphically to tracing operator observables with the density matrix in Hilbert space: they are obtained by phase-space integrals of observables, with the Wigner quasi-probability distribution effectively serving as a measure.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In thermodynamics and statistical mechanics contexts, the term "phase space" has two meanings: for one, it is used in the same sense as in classical mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] If a thermodynamic system consists of *N* particles, then a point in the 6*N*-dimensional phase space describes the dynamic state of every particle in that system, as each particle is associated with 3 position variables and 3 momentum variables.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In this sense, as long as the particles are distinguishable, a point in phase space is said to be a microstate of the system.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] (For indistinguishable particles a microstate consists of a set of *N*! points, corresponding to all possible exchanges of the *N* particles.) *N* is typically on the order of the Avogadro number, thus describing the system at a microscopic level is often impractical.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] This leads to the use of phase space in a different sense.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] The phase space can also refer to the space that is parameterized by the *macroscopic* states of the system, such as pressure, temperature, etc.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] For instance, one may view the pressure–volume diagram or temperature–entropy diagram as describing part of this phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] A point in this phase space is correspondingly called a macrostate.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] There may easily be more than one microstate with the same macrostate.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] For example, for a fixed temperature, the system could have many dynamic configurations at the microscopic level.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] When used in this sense, a phase is a region of phase space where the system in question is in, for example, the liquid phase, or solid phase, etc.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Since there are many more microstates than macrostates, the phase space in the first sense is usually a manifold of much larger dimensions than in the second sense.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Clearly, many more parameters are required to register every detail of the system down to the molecular or atomic scale than to simply specify, say, the temperature or the pressure of the system.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] Phase space is extensively used in nonimaging optics, the branch of optics devoted to illumination.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] It is also an important concept in Hamiltonian optics.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/phase-space] In medicine and bioengineering, the phase space method is used to visualize multidimensional physiological responses.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] More precisely, one considers a periodic orbit with initial conditions within a section of the space, which leaves that section afterwards, and observes the point at which this orbit first returns to the section.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] One then creates a map to send the first point to the second, hence the name *first recurrence map*.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] The transversality of the Poincaré section means that periodic orbits starting on the subspace flow through it and not parallel to it.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] A Poincaré map can be interpreted as a discrete dynamical system with a state space that is one dimension smaller than the original continuous dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] Because it preserves many properties of periodic and quasiperiodic orbits of the original system and has a lower-dimensional state space, it is often used for analyzing the original system in a simpler way.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] In practice this is not always possible as there is no general method to construct a Poincaré map.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] A Poincaré map differs from a recurrence plot in that space, not time, determines when to plot a point.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] For instance, the locus of the Moon when the Earth is at perihelion is a recurrence plot; the locus of the Moon when it passes through the plane perpendicular to the Earth's orbit and passing through the Sun and the Earth at perihelion is a Poincaré map.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] It was used by Michel Hénon to study the motion of stars in a galaxy, because the path of a star projected onto a plane looks like a tangled mess, while the Poincaré map shows the structure more clearly.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] Let (**R**, *M*, *φ*) be a global dynamical system, with **R** the real numbers, *M* the phase space and *φ* the evolution function.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] Let γ be a periodic orbit through a point *p* and *S* be a local differentiable and transversal section of *φ* through *p*, called a **Poincaré section** through *p*.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] Therefore, the solution with initial data $(\theta _{0},r_{0}\neq 1)$ draws a spiral that tends towards the radius 1 circle.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] We can take as Poincaré section for this flow the positive horizontal axis, namely $\Sigma =\{(\theta ,r)\ :\ \theta =0\}$ : obviously we can use r as coordinate on the section.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] Every point in $\Sigma$ returns to the section after a time $t=2\pi$ (this can be understood by looking at the evolution of the angle): we can take as Poincaré map the restriction of $\Phi$ to the section $\Sigma$ computed at the time $2\pi$ , $\Phi _{2\pi }|_{\Sigma }$ .
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] Poincaré maps can be interpreted as a discrete dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] The stability of a periodic orbit of the original system is closely related to the stability of the fixed point of the corresponding Poincaré map.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] Let (**R**, *M*, *φ*) be a differentiable dynamical system with periodic orbit γ through *p*.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] be the corresponding Poincaré map through *p*.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] Per definition this system has a fixed point at *p*.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] The periodic orbit γ of the continuous dynamical system is stable if and only if the fixed point *p* of the discrete dynamical system is stable.
[src:dynamical-systems-math/poincaré-map] The periodic orbit γ of the continuous dynamical system is asymptotically stable if and only if the fixed point *p* of the discrete dynamical system is asymptotically stable.
